The primary purpose of the Path Ambassadors to High Success (PATHS) Scholarship Program was to create compelling new pathways and strengthen existing pathways for academically talented, low-income Colorado high school and community college students to study Computer Science (CS) at the Colorado School of Mines (Mines).  All major project goals were met. Specifically, the PATHS program:

&bull; Increased the number of academically talented, low-income students studying CS in Colorado; 

&bull; Established an active on-campus community to support PATHS Scholars and similar students;

&bull; Increased the retention of similarly situated students;

&bull; Engaged PATHS Scholars to perform CS recruitment and outreach at area high schools and community colleges;

&bull; Evaluated PATHS activities through comparative analysis to provide new insights on best practices for attracting and retaining academically talented, low-income CS students at small engineering universities;

&bull; Broadened participation in CS of historically underrepresented groups; 

&bull; Developed new flexible degree program combining other STEM fields and CS, with specific appeal to low-income students, and 

&bull; Supported the retention of vulnerable students during the COVID-19 pandemic. 

The PATHS program gave scholarships to 52 students, and 21 (40.4%) were students from underrepresented groups: 15 (28.8%) Hispanic Scholars, four (7.7%) Black Scholars, and two (3.8%) Native American Scholars. In addition, 16 (30.8%) of the PATHS Scholars were female. Our overall retention rate (90.9%) was high, due to the support (e.g., community activities, mentoring) that the PATHS program provided. The program activities were chosen based on current literature to create data-driven best practices for recruitment and retention of low-income students. 


Each of the key PATHS objectives assisted in meeting the national need to enhance the quality of a well-educated technical workforce in computing and thereby contributed to maintaining U.S. competitiveness in the global economy. 



